{
    'id': 35,
    'source_dataset': 'ChatMED-Project/RAGCare-QA',
    'tenant_id': 'hospital-general',
    'specialty': 'Endocrinology',
    'complexity': 'basic',
    'case_priority': 'high',
    'case_status': 'review',
    'rag_pipeline': 'Basic RAG',
    'reference': 'Harrison’s Principles of Internal Medicine, 20th ed.',
    'question': '3. Which of the following is true about glucocorticoid-induced osteoporosis? a) It does not develop with glucocorticoid nasal spray use b) Glucocorticoids accelerate resorption but do not reduce bone formation c) We initiate treatment with bisphosphonates when bone mineral density is below –1 SD d) Due to increased calcium excretion, only vitamin D is added, not calcium e) Treatment begins only if glucocorticoids are expected to be given for more than 6 months',
    'text_answer': 'We initiate treatment with bisphosphonates when bone mineral density is below –1 SD',
    'topic_text': '3. Which of the following is true about glucocorticoid-induced osteoporosis? a) It does not develop with glucocorticoid nasal spray use b) Glucocorticoids accelerate resorption but do not reduce bone formation c) We initiate treatment with bisphosphonates when bone mineral density is below –1 SD d) Due to increased calcium excretion, only vitamin D is added, not calcium e) Treatment begins only if glucocorticoids are expected to be given for more than 6 months',
    'context': '“Osteoporosis is the most common long-term complication of systemic glucocorticoid therapy and is both preventable and partially reversible. Glucocorticoid-induced bone loss occurs rapidly within the first 6–12 months of therapy. Both increased bone resorption and decreased bone formation contribute to loss of bone mass.” “Prophylaxis should include adequate intake of calcium (1,200–1,500 mg/day) and vitamin D (800–1,000 IU/day), as well as initiation of bisphosphonate therapy (e.g., alendronate 5–10 mg/day or risedronate 5 mg/day orally) in adults expected to receive the equivalent of ≥5 mg/day of prednisone for ≥3 months.” “Inhaled glucocorticoids (e.g., nasal sprays) have minimal systemic absorption and generally do not cause glucocorticoid-induced osteoporosis.”',
    'text': 'Context: “Osteoporosis is the most common long-term complication of systemic glucocorticoid therapy and is both preventable and partially reversible. Glucocorticoid-induced bone loss occurs rapidly within the first 6–12 months of therapy. Both increased bone resorption and decreased bone formation contribute to loss of bone mass.” “Prophylaxis should include adequate intake of calcium (1,200–1,500 mg/day) and vitamin D (800–1,000 IU/day), as well as initiation of bisphosphonate therapy (e.g., alendronate 5–10 mg/day or risedronate 5 mg/day orally) in adults expected to receive the equivalent of ≥5 mg/day of prednisone for ≥3 months.” “Inhaled glucocorticoids (e.g., nasal sprays) have minimal systemic absorption and generally do not cause glucocorticoid-induced osteoporosis.” Supporting answer: We initiate treatment with bisphosphonates when bone mineral density is below –1 SD'
  },
